    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1053717674" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1053717674" />
    <a title="Daniel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2404888-daniel"><img alt="Daniel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1559046030p2/2404888.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1053717674?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel" href="/user/show/2404888-daniel">Daniel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140621839" href="/book/show/77994.Selected_Short_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2404888-daniel?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1053717674" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9158028838313866289">Perhaps the greatest short story writer of the 19th century. Very few writers bring me as much pleasure as Maupassant, certainly not as quickly. <br/><br/>“Boule de Suif”<br/><br/>About a prostitute who displays more patriotic resistance and self-sacrificing love of her country than France&apos;s bourgeois, aristocratic, and religious classes, which turn their backs on their country in the wake of the Prussian occupation of Normandy.<br/><br/>&quot;In the Spring&quot;<br/><br/>In which a man is on the verge of falling in love with a beautiful girl o</span>
  <span id="freeText9158028838313866289" style="display:none">Perhaps the greatest short story writer of the 19th century. Very few writers bring me as much pleasure as Maupassant, certainly not as quickly. <br /><br />“Boule de Suif”<br /><br />About a prostitute who displays more patriotic resistance and self-sacrificing love of her country than France's bourgeois, aristocratic, and religious classes, which turn their backs on their country in the wake of the Prussian occupation of Normandy.<br /><br />"In the Spring"<br /><br />In which a man is on the verge of falling in love with a beautiful girl on a boat when another man warns him of the dangers of romantic love and effectively prevents the former from making a move.<br /><br />"Graveyard Sisterhood"<br /><br />In which a crafty women picks up men at the cemetery, pretending to be a mourning widow.<br /><br />“La Maison Tellier” <br /><br />In which a group of prostitutes leave their Norman brothel to attend the baptism of their procuress's niece's baptism. They are moved by the purity of the ritual but relieved when they get back to Normandy, where they revel in their profession, relieved that they don't have to be good.<br /><br />“A Ruse”<br /><br />In which a doctor tells a woman patient (one who detests dishonesty in love) about a time where he needed to get the body of one of his female patient's lovers out of her house before her husband came home and of how he managed to get him out without the husband's suspecting. The eponymous ruse is the doctor, as he presents the story as a sale's pitch. When she asks why he told her that horrible story, he says, "to offer my services in case of need."<br /><br />“An Old Man” <br /><br />About an old man who is terrified of dying. <br /><br />“Rust” <br /><br />About a hunting enthusiast who suddenly finds himself in love with a woman but is unsure that he will be able to satisfy her after years of celibacy. He goes to Paris to see if he still has it in him. Even though he gets nervous, he is eventually persuaded by neighbors of his to marry her despite his anxieties. <br /><br />"Two Friends"<br /><br />In which two men who enjoy fishing sacrifice their lives rather than give the Prussians the password that would allow them to enter into the are still held by the French during the Franco-Prussian war. A story about patriotism and friendship. <br /><br />“The Jewels”<br /><br />In which a husband with a wife with a passion for fake jewels discovers that her jewel collection is not so fake--and therefore deduces that she has lovers who give them to her. He has a delightful time with the money he collects from selling the jewels. The irony is that he finds himself happier with his cheating wife (and the jewels she brought in) than with his new wife, which is virtuous but bad-tempered. In other words, the irony is that the happiness of his first marriage stemmed from deception.<br /><br />“The Conservatory” <br /><br />One of my favorites, and SO French. The story of a sour marriage (henpecked husband, dissatisfied wife) that is reanimated when the couple discovers and then spies on their housekeeper having sex with her young lover. <br /><br />“The Matter with André” <br /><br />About a baby boy who prevents his mother from making love to her paramour by crying. Her lover pinches him leaving bruises on him. This gets him to stop crying when he's there but to start when he sees his father. <br /><br />"A Duel"<br /><br />Set after the Prussian victory over France, when the latter was being invaded by their enemy, the story offers a characteristically Maupassantian rendering of a nasty Prussian bullying a Frenchmen into trying to buy him some tobacco on a train. When the latter refuses, the Prussian proceeds to pluck the Frenchman's beard, after which the Frenchman pounces on his abuser. The swaggering Prussian, who boasts that his country will eventually conquer all of Europe, challenges the Frenchman to a duel. The Frenchman agrees and defeats the Prussian. The story is framed by the perspective of a pair of travelling Englishman who look on the battle with fascinated reserve.<br /><br />"In the Woods"<br /><br />The story of a woman who attempts to revive the passion in her marriage by making love to her husband in the woods. Only thing is--they're caught and nearly arrested for indecency. The wife's charming and sad account of their marriage wins the officer over at the end of the day.<br /><br />“Mother Savage” <br /><br />Set in the wake of the French defeat, with Prussians invading Norman villages, this story centers on Mother Savage--a woman who initially takes in four Prussian soldiers. The story begins as a comedy, with the mother treating the young men as her son, and them helping her out with chores around the house. The initial suggestion is that the common humanity of Prussians and French alike eclipses their differences; but this is only a temporary illusion; the realities of war are harsh. Mother Savage soon receives word that her son died in the war, after being blown up by a cannonball. Seeking revenge, she tricks the four Prussians into her barn just before burning it and killing them in an act of revenge. She kills herself just after. The frame story takes place 15 years later, when the narrator asks a villager what happened to the burned down ruins that were once a welcoming barn house. The narrator adores the region and remembers being offered a glass of wine at the house; but this part of the region's history has been supplanted by the gloomy effects of war. A particularly effective use of Maupassant's framing device.<br /><br />“The Signal” <br /><br />What an amusing story--and so Maupassantian. A young woman watches, from across the street, the coy signal that a prostitute makes to men below to reel them into her bedroom. Immediately her intention is understood, and the men come up. The young woman marvels at how a simple shift in expression can succeed in consistently producing the same result. As an experiment, she attempts making the signal herself to a man one day from her window, and--guess what--the man mistakes her for a prostitute, comes up, and begins to aggressively seduce her. The woman tries to resist his advances but finally relents, scared that if she doesn't please him quickly her husband will come home. Later on, her friend counsels her on how to extricate herself from the situation: she tells her to report him to the police and spend the two louis left by the man to buy a present for her husband.<br /><br />“My Uncle Jules” <br /><br />Joseph Devranche and his family are in an extremely tight financial situation because his brother Jules squandered the family fortune. Thankfully Jules has gone to New York, is prospering, and plans to return soon and give them a fraction of his fortune--so he writes them. The family, especially Madame Devranche, excitedly reads his letters to her children and looks forward to the day of their arrival. At the same time, she tries to marry their daughter off and succeeds, in part by telling her suitor about the fortune they plan to inherit from their Uncle Jules. One day they take a little vacation to the English island of Jersey, right off the coast of Normandy. They spot a dirty old man selling oysters to passengers. Guess who it is? Jules. The Devranches are furious. They avoid him so that her daughter's fiancé won't notice that they are related. But the smallest Devranche, a little boy, takes pits on the dingy sailor; he pays for the oysters and leaves a substantial tip--to the fury of his parents. <br /><br />“In the Bedroom” <br /><br />A husband reproaches his wife for supposedly flirting with another man at an evening party. Immediately the wife launches into a fascinating dialogue, reminding him of an affair he had in the past and of a deal he appears to have proposed then, when he told her that all that mattered was that they kept up appearances if that she could take on a lover if she wished. The wife deftly manages to turn her husband's reproach on its head, telling him that she will do as she pleases and take a love when she wants. Moreover, she agrees to sleep with him only if he pays her money. She takes her husband's words to their logical conclusion and asserts that since they are married only in appearance that he is not entitled to her body in private and must pay to have sex with her. The irony is that he insistent resistance makes her husband fall madly in love with her again. He loves her only when she refuses him. <br /><br />“Regret"<br /><br />Another little masterpiece. This one's about a clueless man who waits too long to tell the woman he loves that he loves her. He recalls with horror a scene from the past in which he realizes that his beloved was giving him a chance to seduce him--a chance he turned down because he was afraid he would upset her and because he was married. He visits her after considering this memory in this new light to ask her if she knew he loved her. She mocks him and says of course. It's too late now, though. He missed his chance.<br /><br />“The Necklace” <br /><br />In which a woman (A Madame Bovary type who dreams of aristocratic balls but comes from a lower middle class background) borrows a fake diamond necklace for a party thinking its real. She loses it and buys a similar one for an exorbitant price, which she gives to the friend she borrowed the old necklace from. The family is obliged to sell almost everything they own and spend the next ten years living in near-poverty trying to pay back all the loans. Ten years later, she spots her friend in Paris and reveals why the past ten years have been so bad for her. The friend is shocked and tells her that the original diamond was made of paste.<br /><br />“The Model” <br /><br />“Imprudence” <br /><br />“The Horla” <br /><br />“Mouche”</span>
  <a data-text-id="9158028838313866289" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


