<div id="review_2697988909" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2697988909" />
    <a title="Adam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/73860296-adam"><img alt="Adam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567496185p2/73860296.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2697988909?book_show_action=true">Feb 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam" href="/user/show/73860296-adam">Adam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2697988909" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6733146249361821344">a very grim and bleak perspective on this whole &apos;life&apos; thing. Basically to associate with, maintain and pursue any kind of love: affectionate, brotherly, maternal, romantic or sexual love, will mean we have doomed ourselves to a melancholic state. This is to say that relationships will most certainly lead to a collapse and heart-breaking downfall. The only thing more miserable that pursuing these relationships is not pursuing them. Maupassant reasons that to love is to be miserable, and to not l</span>
  <span id="freeText6733146249361821344" style="display:none">a very grim and bleak perspective on this whole 'life' thing. Basically to associate with, maintain and pursue any kind of love: affectionate, brotherly, maternal, romantic or sexual love, will mean we have doomed ourselves to a melancholic state. This is to say that relationships will most certainly lead to a collapse and heart-breaking downfall. The only thing more miserable that pursuing these relationships is not pursuing them. Maupassant reasons that to love is to be miserable, and to not love is to be even more miserable. To attempt to secure a relationships; the chance at love, at empathy and certainty of pain and heart-ache, is how we can secure the slightest happiness and fleeting internal peace which we yearn for as we are haunted by an existential terror whose impetus is our mortality. Since we will all certainly perish, we must engage with others, no matter the immensity and pervasiveness of their greed, lust, lies, shortsightedness or impracticality. This is in order to squeeze even a singular moment of happiness out of our short, fleeting lives. Even when Death comes for us, it is really only notable to ourselves; everyone else continues to live and we are only concerned with ourselves.<br /><br />Basically, don't be so idiotic to expect anything rejuvenating from relationships, but don't be so practical to not pursue them.<br /><br />Particular favorites of mine include: the Devil, Regret, The Convert, The Conservatory, Two Friends, In the Spring. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6733146249361821344" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


